				"string" : "## Overview\n\n{{gtClass:GtRrRunnerLogTimingAnalyzer}} is a class that reads log files from test suite executions and extracts timing statistics. It processes beacon signals from log files and calculates various timing metrics, storing them in {{gtClass:GtRrRunnerLogTimingStats}}.\n\n## Architecture\n\n### Related Classes\n\n- {{gtClass:GtRrRunnerLogTimingStat}} - Holds individual statistical data points and computes statistics (average, standard deviation, coefficient of variation)\n- {{gtClass:GtRrRunnerLogTimingStats}} - A container (dictionary-based) that holds multiple named {{gtClass:GtRrRunnerLogTimingStat}} instances. Can be persisted to/loaded from STON files\n- {{gtClass:GtBeaconJsonLogReader}} - Reads log files and deserializes beacon signals\n- {{gtClass:BeaconSignal}} - Base class for all signals; provides `timestamp` for timing calculations\n\n### Key Instance Variables\n\n- `filename` - The log file to analyze (a FileReference)\n- `signals` - Cached collection of signals loaded from the log file (lazily loaded)\n- `timingStats` - The {{gtClass:GtRrRunnerLogTimingStats}} instance being populated\n\n## How to Add a New Statistic\n\nAdding a new statistic follows a consistent pattern with three steps:\n\n### Step 1: Create Signal Finder Method(s)\n\nSearch for existing signal finder methods first to avoid duplicating logic. If you need a new method, place it in the `private - signals` protocol. For examples of the expected structure, see {{gtMethod:GtRrRunnerLogTimingAnalyzer>>#firstJobStartupSignal}} and {{gtMethod:GtRrRunnerLogTimingAnalyzer>>#lastTaskCompletedSignal}}.\n\n### Step 2: Create Calculation Method\n\nCreate a method that calculates the statistic value and place it in the `private - statistics` protocol. Return `nil` if the required signals are not found. For examples of expected structure and error handling, see {{gtMethod:GtRrRunnerLogTimingAnalyzer>>#calculateFirstTaskQueuedTime}} and {{gtMethod:GtRrRunnerLogTimingAnalyzer>>#calculateAverageTaskTime}}.\n\n### Step 3: Create Update Method\n\nCreate a method that updates the timing stats with the calculated value and place it in the `statistics` protocol. For examples of expected structure and error handling, see {{gtMethod:GtRrRunnerLogTimingAnalyzer>>#updateFirstTaskQueuedTimeStat}} and {{gtMethod:GtRrRunnerLogTimingAnalyzer>>#updateAverageTaskTimeStat}}.\n\n### Step 4: Register in analyze Method\n\nRegister the new update method in {{gtMethod:GtRrRunnerLogTimingAnalyzer>>#analyze}} alongside the existing updates. For an example of method organization, see {{gtMethod:GtRrRunnerLogTimingAnalyzer>>#analyze}}.\n\n\n## Common Signal Classes\n\nWhen adding statistics, you'll likely work with signals that are subclasses of {{gtClass:BeaconSignal}}. Key properties available on all signals:\n\n- `timestamp` - A DateAndTime when the signal was created\n- `processId` - The process ID that created the signal\n\nTo find available signal classes for RemoteRunner, search for subclasses of relevant base signal classes or search for classes with names starting with `GtRr`.\n\n## Testing The Statistics\n\n{{gtMethod:GtRrRunnerLogTimingAnalyzerExamples>>#analyzeAllSampleLogs}} demonstrates loading logs from a file and verifying that they are correct.\n\n## Best Practices\n\n1. **Naming**: Use descriptive, human-readable names for statistics (e.g., 'First task queued time' not 'ftqt')\n\n2. **Null safety**: Always check for nil signals before calculating; return nil from calculation methods if data is unavailable\n\n3. **Units**: Document the units in method comments; prefer milliseconds for consistency\n\n4. **Protocol organization**:\n   - `private - signals` for signal finder methods\n   - `private - statistics` for calculation methods\n   - `statistics` for update methods\n   - `api` for public entry points\n\n5. **Reusability**: If multiple statistics need the same signal, create a single finder method and reuse it"
			}
		]
	},
